URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS786414082	2019-07-21 11:09:40	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			2			Unknown Sex, Juvenile (1); Male, Adult (1)	United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Clark	US-NV-003		33			Desert Breeze Park	L3250276	H	36.1251280	-115.2767783	2019-07-18	18:55:00	obsr273117	S58284627	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	50	1.304		1	1		1	1	0		Urban park of manicured lawn area for recreation use, exotic trees for shade, and xeric landscaping on the park's margin. A large parcel of remnant natural, but disturbed, desert habitat is to the south of the park. Temperature was in the 90s, sunny.	Initially saw a pewee sized Tyranid ( definitely smaller than a phoebe and larger than a typical Empidonax )  in the vicinity of the SE portion of the park, near the playground with the bright blue fence. The bird fit the description of a juvenile vermilion flycatcher; rotund body shape, tail that is short and darker than the mantle, streaked breast, diffuse eye stripe. I did not see any yellow tones to the vent and lower belly of the bird. A few minutes later I viewed an adult male vermilion flycatcher in the same area. This bird was bright red underside, chin, forehead and crown, with a dark chocolate colored back, wings, tail, nape with an extension forwards to the bill in the form of an eye stripe.  An adult female VEFL was not observed at this time. There was a lot of bird activity at the time, dusk was approaching, so I may have missed additional VEFLs in the immediate area. Due to the presence of a juvenile bird and an adult male it is most likely that a family unit is present, possibly having bred here, or in close proximity.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS56293068	2017-04-18 17:05:33	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			1				United States	US	Nevada	US-NV	Nye	US-NV-023	US-NV_977	33	USFWS_350		Ash Meadows NWR HQ	L388900	H	36.4204294	-116.3299853	1965-04-14	06:15:00	obsr56422	S4058241	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	405	4.023	4.0469	2	1		0	1	0		Potash Springs, Longstreet Springs, Frog Springs and Rodgers Springs. Habitat varies, see bird notes. 55F, warm, sunny. This is a Desert Ecology Class, Chico State College. We are in the northern end of Ash Meadows in western Nevada. It is a hot, arid land with steep rising mountains which almost totally lack any type of vegetation. Potash Springs, one mile north of Longstreet Springs was where we camped. The springs are an oasis in the desert. Vegetation is very sparse and located primarily around these springs. Plants are Tamarisk, willow, cottonwood,  and some sedges. Away from water the basic shrubs are Mesquite. Some succulents and Creosote present. Buildings at the various sights were built around 1860. Potash Springs is approx. 4 miles west of SR29 and about 10 miles south of Lathrop Wells, NV. Frog Springs and Rodger Springs are located inbetween Potash and Longstreet Springs.----Observers: Myself and Dr. Dempsey----Footnote: 8PM, Lou Davis and I went north 19 miles to some sand dunes. Only insect present were 3 beetles, some grubs and 5 Dune Crickets. These crickets never before found this far north. All beetles proceeding up dunes, none down. When sand was pushed down, beetles always remained on top or ahead of moving sand. 10PM	Longstreet Springs, Desert: Oasis/Alkali

Has red crest. Dark brown back and tail and wings. Red underparts. Black mask. A Scarlet Tanager male would be a rare bird to Nevada. The Scarlet Tanager has a all red head that is round with no crest like the Vermilion Flycatcher. Black wings and tail. Has no black mask like the Vermilion Flycatcher. Eye is dark in a plain red face where a Vermilion Flycatcher has a dark eye within a black mask.  Bill on a male Scarlet Tanager is dark and larger than a male Vermilion Flycatcher. A Vermilion Flycatcher has a small dark bill.
